\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:introduction}
Type {\uppercase\expandafter{\romannumeral {1}\relax}}a supernovae (SNe) are thermonuclear explosions of carbon oxygen white dwarfs (WDs). Since the majority of them (normal Type {\uppercase\expandafter{\romannumeral {1}\relax}}a SNe) 
follow a well-established empirical relation between variation of their peak magnitudes and lightcurve shapes \citep{Phillips1993}, they are standardized
to measure cosmological distances (see \citealt{GL2011} for a review). However, the underlying progenitor systems and explosion mechanisms of
Type {\uppercase\expandafter{\romannumeral {1}\relax}}a SNe remain poorly understood. 

Recent observations have provided mounting evidence that Type {\uppercase\expandafter{\romannumeral {1}\relax}}a SNe have multiple progenitor channels (see \citealt{mmn14}
for a review). In the single-degenerate (SD) channel, a WD accretes material from a companion star and explodes when its mass approaches
the Chandrasekhar limit \citep{wi73}. This channel is supported by possible detections of companion stars in pre- or post-SN images
\citep{mjf+14,fmj+14}, likely signatures of supernova-companion collisions \citep{ckh+15,mbv+15}, and observations of variable 
\ion{Na}{1}\,D absorption \citep{pcc+07,sgs+14}. In the double-degenerate (DD) channel, in contrast, two WDs collide or merge in 
a binary or even triple system to produce a Type {\uppercase\expandafter{\romannumeral {1}\relax}}a SN \citep[e.g.,][]{ni85,kkd+13}. This channel is consistent with observations of 
two nearby Type {\uppercase\expandafter{\romannumeral {1}\relax}}a SN2011fe and SN2014J \citep[e.g.,][]{lbp+11,BDd2012,ssp+13,mpk+14,kff+14,gks+15,lnt+15}. 

Unlike the SD channel, SNe from the DD channel may have ejecta mass beyond the Chandrasekhar limit (super-Chandrasekhar Type {\uppercase\expandafter{\romannumeral {1}\relax}}a SNe).
In fact, more than a handful of SNe were found to have total ejecta masses significantly exceeding the Chandrasekhar limit
\citep{hsn+06,hgp+07,yqw+10,ykk+09,saa+10,sgl+11,sct+14}. However, these super-Chandrasekhar SNe show distinctive characteristics compared to normal
events: they are over-luminous in both the optical and UV, implying a large amount of synthesized $^{56}$Ni. They show low expansion velocities and long
rise times, leading to massive ejecta. They also show persistent absorption from unburned carbon. If they originate from the same DD systems as some 
normal Type {\uppercase\expandafter{\romannumeral {1}\relax}}a SNe, then an intermediate case is needed to bridge the super-Chandrasekhar and normal Type {\uppercase\expandafter{\romannumeral {1}\relax}}a SNe. 

In this paper, we present observations of a peculiar Type {\uppercase\expandafter{\romannumeral {1}\relax}}a SN, iPTF13asv, that shares observational characteristics with both super-Chandrasekhar and normal
Type {\uppercase\expandafter{\romannumeral {1}\relax}}a SN. It was discovered with $r=20.54\pm0.16$\,mag at $\alpha=16^h22^m43^s.19$, 
$\delta=+18^\circ57^\prime35{\hbox{$\ \!\!^{\prime\prime}$}}.0$ (J2000) in the vicinity of galaxy SDSS\,J$162243.02{+}185733.8$ on UTC 2013 May $1.44$ (hereafter May 
$1.44$) by the intermediate Palomar Transient Factory (iPTF; \citealt{LKD2009,RKL2009}). Nothing was
seen at the same location down to 5-$\sigma$ detection thresholds of $r\simeq 21.0$\,mag on images taken on April 30.5 and earlier. iPTF13asv was
independently discovered and classified as a peculiar Type {\uppercase\expandafter{\romannumeral {1}\relax}}a by \citet{CBET3543}, and was designated as SN2013cv. 

This paper is organized as follows: the observational data is present in \S\ref{sec:obs}. The photometric and spectroscopic 
properties are analyzed in \S\ref{sec:analysis}, and we construct its bolometric lightcurve and estimate the total ejecta mass in \S\ref{sec:mass}. 
A discussions about the nature of iPTF13asv is given in \S\ref{sec:discussion} and our conclusions are summarized in \S\ref{sec:conclusion}. 

Throughout this paper, we adopt a Hubble Constant $H_0=67.77\,{\rm km}\,{\rm s}^{-1}\,{\rm Mpc}^{-1}$ \citep{Planck2013}. 
The apparent host galaxy of iPTF13asv does not have a redshift-independent 
distance measurement in the NASA/IPAC Extragalactic Database. Thus we calculate a distance modulus of 36.07\,mag by using its redshift
$0.036$. The peculiar motion of the host galaxy at ${\sim}100\,\rm{km}\,\rm{s}^{-1}$ introduces an uncertainty of $\lessapprox0.05$\,mag to the distance modulus. 
The Galactic line-of-sight extinction is $E(B-V)=0.045$ \citep{SF2011}. We correct for the Galactic extinction by using the parametrized model in
\citet{ftz99} with $R_V=3.1$. 


