The absence of iron at early phases indicates that synthesized iron group elements are confined in low-velocity regions of the ejecta. Since the iron
group elements are the main absorbers of photons below $3500$\,\AA, the lack of iron group elements in fast-moving ejecta effectively reduces the UV 
opacity at early phases. In fact, as shown in the dark gray region in Figure \ref{fig:specZoomIn}, the flux of iPTF13asv below $3500$\,\AA\ is seemingly
stronger than those of SN2011fe at early phases. We did not trigger \textit{Swift} observations at early phases of iPTF13asv, because it is about 160\,Mpc
away from us. Our experience shows that \textit{Swift} UV observations are usually sensitive to Type {\uppercase\expandafter{\romannumeral {1}\relax}}a SNe within 100\,Mpc. Otherwise, 
\textit{Swift} observations at these phases would be perfectly suited to show the UV flux difference. 

The spectral sequence in Figure \ref{fig:specZoomIn} also shows that the iron features start to emerge in iPTF13asv about a week before maximum. 
Around maximum, the spectra of iPTF13asv show similar features to both normal and super-Chandrasekhar events
(Figure \ref{fig:specAtPeak}). The expansion velocities of iPTF13asv, as indicated by \ion{Si}{2}\,6355 minima, are similar to those of both SN2011fe and 
SN2012cg and higher than that of SN2009dc.

We further compare the expansion velocity evolution of iPTF13asv to a sample of normal and super-Chandrasekhar events (Figure \ref{fig:velocity}). 
The velocities are measured by fitting a Gaussian profile to the iPTF13asv spectra around the \ion{Si}{2}\,6355 features. 
The continuum components are removed by a linear regression to regions at both sides of the absorption features. 
As can be seen in Figure \ref{fig:velocity}, iPTF13asv has a low expansion velocity and a shallow velocity gradient, compared to normal
Type {\uppercase\expandafter{\romannumeral {1}\relax}}a SNe. Around maximum, the expansion velocity of iPTF13asv is $\simeq10,000\,\rm{km}\,\rm{s}^{-1}$ and the velocity 
gradient is roughly zero. The low expansion velocity and shallow velocity gradient of iPTF13asv is usually seen in super-Chandrasekhar events.

